I. Adding the meta-zuboard layer to your build
=================================================

Run 'bitbake-layers add-layer meta-zuboard'

II. JTAG provisioning image
===========================

Build the RAM-resident provisioning image and the production WIC together:

  bitbake mncos-jtag-image

The complete bundle is exported to:

  build/export/jtag-tftpboot

Use that directory as the TFTP server root. From the same directory, start the
JTAG boot with XSDB. The hw_server and TFTP server addresses are required; the
temporary static board address is optional:

  xsdb load-jtag-image.tcl <hw-server-ip> <tftp-server-ip> [board-ip]

For example:

  xsdb load-jtag-image.tcl 127.0.0.1 192.168.1.10

With no board-ip argument, U-Boot obtains the board address through DHCP. DHCP
autoload is disabled, so it only configures networking; the loader-provided
TFTP server address remains authoritative. A static board address is optional:

  xsdb load-jtag-image.tcl 127.0.0.1 192.168.1.10 192.168.1.20

The TCL script writes a one-shot marker before starting U-Boot. U-Boot consumes
the marker and automatically runs "run tftpbootstep". Normal production boots
do not write the marker and keep their existing boot behavior.

The TCL arguments configure U-Boot for that one JTAG boot without rebuilding
or saving the environment.

To JTAG/TFTP boot and test the full mncos-image-minimal rootfs instead, build
that target and run the same loader from build/export/tftpboot. The directory
determines which rootfs.cpio.gz.u-boot is downloaded; the U-Boot marker and
runtime U-Boot IP override behavior are shared by both images.

After the provisioning Linux boots, write the verified production WIC to the
detected non-removable eMMC device with:

  mncos-flash-emmc

If the Linux-side TFTP server differs from the build-time default, pass it to
the flashing utility as well:

  mncos-flash-emmc --server 192.168.1.10

The provisioning Linux has separate build-time network defaults in
meta-mncos. They can be overridden in local.conf when that RAM image itself
needs a different static address:

  MNCOS_TFTP_SERVER_IP = "172.30.19.19"
  MNCOS_TFTP_CLIENT_IP = "172.30.19.20"
  MNCOS_TFTP_PREFIX_LENGTH = "24"

The utility downloads target.wic.xz and target.wic.xz.sha256 over TFTP, checks
the SHA-256 and XZ stream, verifies the target capacity, and requires an ERASE
confirmation before writing. Use --target only when automatic eMMC detection
cannot select exactly one device.

The board device tree must enable the eMMC controller and expose its user-area
block device to Linux. The current zub1cg.dtsi explicitly enables only sdhci1
for the SD card, so eMMC pinmux/controller support is still a board prerequisite.
